CASPER: Volume 6 — Planning Engine Specification

Version: 2.0.0-PLAN

Classification: Restricted — Autonomous Cognitive Systems Engineering Division

PART I: Planning Philosophy

1.1 Goal-Oriented Cognition and Hierarchical Planning

In the CASPER architecture, cognitive execution is formulated as the systematic
minimization of variational free energy over a temporal horizon. Natural
language user intents (e.g., "Secure a backend developer job before December")
are highly complex, non-deterministic objectives containing vast latent
dependencies. To resolve these intents, the system relies on Hierarchical
Goal-Oriented Cognition. High-level goals must be systematically decomposed into
nested lattices of objectives, projects, tasks, and primitive execution steps.

+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                 L0: USER INTENT                                 |
|                     "Secure backend developer job by Dec"                       |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
                                         |
                                         v
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                  L1: GOALS                                      |
|            - Build Resume      - Apply to Roles      - Study DSA                |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
                                         |
                                         v
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                L2: OBJECTIVES                                   |
|                          - Complete DSA Practice                                |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
                                         |
                                         v
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                  L3: PLANS                                      |
|                    - Solve 50 Array & String Problems                           |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
                                         |
                                         v
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                  L4: TASKS                                      |
|                      - Complete Two-Sum on LeetCode                             |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
                                         |
                                         v
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                 L5: ACTIONS                                     |
|                     - Open Browser and Navigate to URL                          |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
                                         |
                                         v
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                L6: TOOL CALLS                                   |
|                - Playwright click target selector coordinates                   |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------+

1.2 Mathematical Formulation of Active Inference Planning

The Planning Engine selects a policy (plan) \pi that minimizes Expected Free
Energy G(\pi) over a temporal horizon \tau \in [t, T]:

G(\pi) = \sum_{\tau=t}^{T} G(\pi, \tau)

The Expected Free Energy of a policy at a specific future step \tau is
decomposed into epistemic (information-seeking) and pragmatic (goal-seeking)
value:

G(\pi, \tau) \approx -\underbrace{\mathbb{E}_{q(o_\tau, s_\tau \mid \pi)} \left[ \ln p(o_\tau \mid m) - \ln q(o_\tau \mid \pi) \right]}_{\text{Pragmatic Value (Goal Directed)}} - \underbrace{\mathbb{E}_{q(s_\tau \mid \pi)} \left[ \mathbb{E}_{q(o_\tau \mid s_\tau, \pi)} \left[ \ln q(s_\tau \mid o_\tau, \pi) - \ln q(s_\tau \mid \pi) \right] \right]}_{\text{Epistemic Value (Information Seeking)}}

Where:

  - s_\tau represents the hidden environmental state at step \tau.
  - o_\tau represents the sensory/tool observations at step \tau.
  - p(o_\tau \mid m) represents the prior target preference profile (the goal
    specification) defined by the user context m.
  - q(s_\tau \mid \pi) is the variational belief state distribution over latent
    environmental variables under policy \pi.
  - q(o_\tau \mid s_\tau, \pi) is the predicted likelihood of observation o_\tau
    given state s_\tau.

Through this mathematical formulation, CASPER's Planning Engine naturally
balances exploration (e.g., searching directory structures, testing API
endpoints) with exploitation (e.g., writing files, completing database
transactions).

1.3 Classical AI Planning vs. Modern LLM-Assisted Planning

Classical planning paradigms—such as STRIPS, PDDL, and Hierarchical Task
Networks (HTN)—rely on deterministic state representations, closed-world
assumptions, and pre-defined operator libraries. These methods provide absolute
correctness and validation but fail in highly unstructured environments (e.g.,
standard web browsing or codebase exploration) due to state-space explosion and
missing operational definitions.

LLM-based planners exhibit vast domain knowledge and fluid intent understanding
but suffer from catastrophic compounding errors, hallucination of tool
capabilities, and lack of deterministic validation checks.

CASPER resolves this trade-off using a Hybrid Neuro-Symbolic Planning
architecture. LLMs act as probabilistic Proposal Engines that draft candidate
state transformations, while deterministic engines (HTN compilers, CSP solvers,
and Pearl structural causal models) validate, prune, and schedule the generated
steps.

                    [HYBRID NEURO-SYMBOLIC PLANNING]
                                   |
         +-------------------------+-------------------------+
         |                                                   |
         v                                                   v
[Probabilistic Proposal Engine]                     [Deterministic Guard Engine]
  - Large Language Model (LLM)                        - HTN Compilers & CSP Solvers
  - Generates candidate tasks                         - Validates preconditions & rules
  - Translates user intent                            - Schedules execution sequences

