   v
L2: Objectives (Milestones / Concrete Quantifiable Deliverables)
   |
   | [Dependency Resolved via DAG Builder]
   v
L3: Plans (Sequenced DAGs of Conditional Tasks)
   |
   | [Scheduled by Task Scheduler]
   v
L4: Tasks (Unitary Operations Assigned to Specific Agents)
   |
   | [Instantiated as Actuator Invocations]
   v
L5: Actions (Logical Domain Operations: Web, File, API)
   |
   | [Translated to Specific Protocol Drivers]
   v
L6: Tool Calls (Syntactical Tool Payload Execution)
   |
   | [Executed in Secure Container]
   v
L7: Execution Steps (Raw Operating System I/O, IPC Messages)

PART IV: Planning Manager

4.1 Internal Scheduler and Queue Architecture

The Planning Manager hosts a multi-priority FIFO/EDF scheduling queue. The
internal thread pool dynamically scales planning operations based on systemic
load metrics.

                  +--------------------------------------------+
                  |               PLANNING QUEUES              |
                  +--------------------------------------------+
                  |                                            |
                  |  [ High Priority Queue ] ---> Priority >= 6|
                  |  - Interrupt and emergency plans           |
                  |                                            |
                  |  [ Active Queue ] -----------> Priority 3-5|
                  |  - Active user goals                       |
                  |                                            |
                  |  [ Background Queue ] -------> Priority 1-2|
                  |  - Routine indexing and maintenance        |
                  |                                            |
                  +--------------------------------------------+

4.2 Dynamic Throttling & Budgets

Resource consumption is controlled using a multi-dimensional budget system to
prevent infinite reasoning loops:

\text{BudgetRemaining} = \text{BudgetLimit} - \sum (\text{Usage}_{Tokens} \cdot w_T + \text{Usage}_{Time} \cdot w_t + \text{Usage}_{Cost} \cdot w_c)

If the calculated budget index falls below safety thresholds, the Planning
Manager pauses execution, saves the active state, and prompts the user for
authorization.

PART V: Goal Compiler

5.1 Goal State Machine

stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Uncompiled : User intent received
    Uncompiled --> Normalizing : Run NLP cleanup
    Normalizing --> Validating : Parse structural assertions
    
    Validating --> Validated : Check preconditions & safety rules
    Validating --> Failed : Constraints violation / Contradiction
    
    Validated --> Active : Dispatch to Task Decomposer
    Active --> Suspended : Preemption interrupt
    Suspended --> Active : Focus recovery
    
    Active --> Merged : Combine similar goals
    Active --> Split : Divide complex objectives
    
    Active --> Fulfilled : Goal verification complete
    Active --> Aborted : Manual cancel / Safety breach
    
    Failed --> [*]
    Fulfilled --> [*]
    Aborted --> [*]

5.2 Goal State Representation

A Goal State is represented mathematically as a target vector \mathbf{g}^*
within a multi-dimensional state space \mathcal{S}. The goal is achieved when
the distance metric between the estimated current state \mathbf{s}_t and the
target \mathbf{g}^* falls below threshold \epsilon:

d(\mathbf{s}_t, \mathbf{g}^*) = \sqrt{(\mathbf{s}_t - \mathbf{g}^*)^T \mathbf{W} (\mathbf{s}_t - \mathbf{g}^*)} < \epsilon

Where \mathbf{W} is a positive-definite diagonal matrix representing the
priority weights assigned to different state variables.

PART VI: Task Decomposition

6.1 Recursive HTN Task Decomposition Loop

flowchart TD
    A[Task Decomposer Activated] --> B[Retrieve Compound Task Node]
    B --> C[Fetch applicable expansion methods from Domain Schema]
    C --> D{Verify Preconditions}
    
    D -->|Passed| E[Decompose into sub-tasks]
    D -->|Failed| F[Try next expansion method]
    
    E --> G{Are sub-tasks primitive?}
    G -->|Yes| H[Register tasks as executable Action Steps]
    G -->|No| B
    
    F --> I{Any methods left?}
    I -->|Yes| C
    I -->|No| J[Trigger plan repair loop]

6.2 HTN Expansion Algorithm

procedure DecomposeTask(task, state, plan)
    if is_primitive(task) then
        if check_preconditions(task, state) then
            append(plan, task)
            state = apply_effects(task, state)
            return true, state, plan
        else
            return false, state, plan
        end
    else
        methods = get_applicable_methods(task, state)
        for each method in methods do
            subtasks = get_subtasks(method)
            temp_state = copy(state)
            temp_plan = copy(plan)
            success = true
            
            for each subtask in subtasks do
                success, temp_state, temp_plan = DecomposeTask(subtask, temp_state, temp_plan)
                if not success then break end
            end
            
            if success then
                return true, temp_state, temp_plan
            end
        end
        return false, state, plan
    end
end procedure

PART VII: Planning Algorithms

7.1 Algorithmic Selection Criteria

| Scenario                         | Primary Algorithm    | Alternative Algorithm | Complexity        | Selection Trigger                                   |
| :------------------------------- | :------------------- | :-------------------- | :---------------- | :-------------------------------------------------- |
| **Highly Structured Workflows**  | HTN (Hierarchical)   | STRIPS / PDDL         | $O(B^D)$          | Standard system maintenance, template-matched tasks |
| **Open-Ended Web Search**        | GOAP (Goal-Oriented) | A\* Search            | $O(V \log V + E)$ | Web navigation, e-commerce checkout loops           |
| **Concurrent Tool Execution**    | POP (Partial-Order)  | Dependency Sorter     | NP-Hard           | Multi-agent pipelines, concurrent file indexing     |
| **Complex Risk Evaluation**      | MCTS (Monte Carlo)   | Branch & Bound        | $O(N \cdot M)$    | Sandbox evaluations, high-budget runs               |
| **Resource & Budget Throttling** | CSP Backtracking     | Dynamic Weights       | $O(B^D)$          | Safety checks, strict budget-capped tasks           |

PART VIII: Plan Objects

The following JSON schema defines the core verifiable data structure used to
track planning runs and execution steps within CASPER.

8.1 Planning Session Schema (planning_session.json)

{
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
  "title": "PlanningSession",
  "type": "object",
  "required": [
    "session_id",
    "goal_id",
    "status",
    "budget",
    "plan_graph",
    "telemetry"
  ],
  "properties": {
    "session_id": { "type": "string", "format": "uuid" },
    "goal_id": { "type": "string", "format": "uuid" },
    "status": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["PENDING", "COMPILING", "VALIDATING", "RUNNING", "SUSPENDED", "SUCCESSFUL", "FAILED"]
    },
    "budget": {
      "type": "object",
      "required": ["max_tokens", "max_cost_usd", "max_time_seconds"],
      "properties": {
        "max_tokens": { "type": "integer", "minimum": 0 },
        "max_cost_usd": { "type": "number", "minimum": 0.0 },
        "max_time_seconds": { "type": "integer", "minimum": 0 }
      }
    },
    "plan_graph": {
      "type": "object",
      "required": ["nodes", "edges"],
      "properties": {
        "nodes": {
          "type": "array",
          "items": {
            "type": "object",
            "required": ["node_id", "type", "description", "preconditions", "effects"],
            "properties": {
              "node_id": { "type": "string", "format": "uuid" },
              "type": { "type": "string", "enum": ["GOAL", "OBJECTIVE", "TASK", "ACTION"] },
              "description": { "type": "string" },
              "preconditions": { "type": "object" },
              "effects": { "type": "object" }
            }
          }
        },
        "edges": {
          "type": "array",
          "items": {
            "type": "object",
            "required": ["source_id", "target_id", "relation_type"],
            "properties": {
              "source_id": { "type": "string", "format": "uuid" },
              "target_id": { "type": "string", "format": "uuid" },
              "relation_type": { "type": "string", "enum": ["PARENT_OF", "PREREQUISITE_FOR", "TEMPORAL_BEFORE"] }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "telemetry": {
      "type": "object",
      "required": ["span_id", "trace_id"],
      "properties": {
        "span_id": { "type": "string" },
        "trace_id": { "type": "string" }
      }
    }
  }
}

