9.1 Graph Traversal and Loop Pruning

The planning graph is compiled into a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) for
processing. The dependency builder validates paths using Tarjan's Strongly
Connected Components (SCC) algorithm to detect and prune cyclic dependencies
before execution starts.

PART X: Planning Indexing

CASPER indexes task templates and historical plan runs using an embedded vector
index (HNSW) alongside local relational databases to ensure fast, low-latency
lookups:

flowchart TD
    A[New Task Request] --> B[Generate Task Semantic Embedding]
    B --> C[Query HNSW Vector Index]
    C --> D[Identify closest matching historical templates]
    D --> E[Query local relational DB for performance logs]
    E --> F[Select and compile target planning template]

PART XI: Planning Pipeline

This sequence diagram illustrates how CASPER compiles, validates, schedules, and
dispatches a planning session:

sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Core as Executive Kernel Core
    participant Mgr as Planning Manager
    participant Goal as Goal Compiler
    participant Dec as Task Decomposer
    participant Res as Resource Planner
    participant Risk as Risk Planner
    participant Dis as Planning Dispatcher

    Core->>Mgr: Start Planning Session (User Intent)
    activate Mgr
    Mgr->>Goal: Normalise & Compile Intent
    Goal-->>Mgr: Return Validated Goal Object
    
    Mgr->>Dec: Decompose Goal into HTN Tree
    activate Dec
    Dec->>Dec: Run recursive task expansions
    Dec-->>Mgr: Return Decomposed Task Graph
    deactivate Dec
    
    Mgr->>Res: Allocate budgets & check resource bounds
    Res-->>Mgr: Return Resource Allocation Map
    
    Mgr->>Risk: Run causal risk checks & policy audits
    activate Risk
    Risk->>Risk: Check hard constraints & budget caps
    Risk-->>Mgr: Return Policy Verdict (Approved)
    deactivate Risk
    
    Mgr->>Dis: Dispatch Tasks to Active Queues
    Dis-->>Mgr: Return Session Task Stream
    Mgr-->>Core: Signal Ready State & Stream Run Progress
    deactivate Mgr

PART XII: Constraint Engine

                            [CONSTRAINT SOLVER (CSP)]
                                           |
          +--------------------------------+--------------------------------+
          |                                |                                |
          v                                v                                v
   [Hard Constraint Guards]     [Soft Constraint Weights]        [AC-3 Consistency Engine]
    - Direct policy rules        - Evaluates path costs           - Explores valid domains
    - Enforces system bounds     - Balances budget targets        - Prunes invalid states

The Constraint Engine models tasks as Constraint Satisfaction Problems, ensuring
plans align with hard boundaries (e.g., security policies, budget limits) before
execution starts:

\text{Minimize } \sum_{j \in T} \mathcal{C}(x_j) \quad \text{subject to} \quad \mathbf{A}x \leq \mathbf{b}, \quad x_i \in \mathcal{D}_i

The solver uses the Arc Consistency 3 (AC-3) algorithm to prune invalid domains
before running backtracking searches, minimizing processing latencies on complex
plans.

PART XIII: Temporal Planning

The Temporal Planner schedules and coordinates execution steps using Allen's
Interval Relations to map deadlines and dependencies:

+-------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                        ALLEN'S INTERVAL RELATIONS                       |
+-------------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                                                                         |
|  [ Before ]       | Task A |  --->  | Task B |                          |
|  [ Meets ]        | Task A || Task B |                                  |
|  [ Overlaps ]     | Task A |                                            |
|                        | Task B |                                       |
|  [ Starts ]       | A |                                                 |
|                   | Task B |                                            |
|  [ During ]         | A |                                               |
|                   | Task B |                                            |
|  [ Finishes ]         | A |                                             |
|                   | Task B |                                            |
|  [ Equals ]       | Task A |                                            |
|                   | Task B |                                            |
|                                                                         |
+-------------------------------------------------------------------------+

PART XIV: Resource Planning

The Resource Planner manages system allocations, balancing compute capacities,
token allowances, and cost budgets across concurrency slots:

flowchart TD
    A[Task Step Dispatched] --> B[Evaluate Resource Demands]
    B --> C{Verify Budget Limits}
    
    C -->|Within Limits| D[Allocate Resource Tokens]
    C -->|Limit Exceeded| E[Halt Task & Notify User]
    
    D --> F[Run Sandboxed execution worker]
    F --> G[Log resource, token, CPU & cost usage]
    G --> H[Update budget metrics]
    H --> B

PART XV: Plan Optimization

The Plan Optimizer identifies and implements structural efficiencies across
compiled planning lattices:

  - DAG Pruning: Automatically identifies and removes redundant nodes and dead
    branches, reducing unnecessary tasks.
  - Task Parallelization: Group independent tasks for concurrent run inside open
    worker slots, minimizing overall latency.
  - Token and Cost Reduction: Optimizes model query context lengths, using
    semantic caching to save token costs.

PART XVI: Plan Repair

                               [PLAN REPAIR ENGINE]
                                        |
         +------------------------------+------------------------------+
         |                              |                              |
         v                              v                              v
[Failure Monitor Daemon]       [Subtree Patching Loop]        [Dynamic Rollbacks Engine]
 - Identifies step exceptions   - Replaces failed sub-plans    - Resets modified environments
 - Pauses execution threads     - Maintains parent plan nodes  - Restores baseline variables

When an execution step fails, the Plan Repair Engine patches the task graph
locally, avoiding complete re-planning runs:

flowchart TD
    A[Step Execution Failure] --> B[Pause Plan Execution Thread]
    B --> C[Isolate Failed Node in Task Tree]
    C --> D[Retrieve local environmental variables]
    
    D --> E{Is local repair possible?}
    E -->|Yes| F[Generate alternative HTN subtree]
    F --> G[Patch Task Lattice & Resume Execution]
    
    E -->|No| H[Trigger full rollback & seek user input]

PART XVII: Simulation Engine

The Simulation Engine runs sandboxed, counterfactual dry-runs to predict plan
outcomes and assess risks before physical execution starts:

flowchart TD
    A[Proposed Action Plan] --> B[Initialize counterfactual sandboxes]
    B --> C[Run Monte Carlo rollouts]
    C --> D[Evaluate execution risks & outcomes]
    D --> E{Risk scores within safety bounds?}
    
    E -->|Yes| F[Approve Plan Execution]
    E -->|No| G[Halt, Adjust Parameters, Re-simulate]

PART XVIII: Memory Integration

The Planning Engine continuously interfaces with Volume 4's multi-tier Memory
Engine, using past lessons and preference data to guide plan synthesis:

sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Plan as Planning Engine Core
    participant Mem as Memory Routing Bus
    participant Active as Working Memory Cache
    participant STM as STM SQLite Store
    participant LTM as LTM Vector & Graph DB

    Plan->>Mem: Query Context & Preferences (Task: DSA Practice)
    activate Mem
    Mem->>Active: Retrieve current operational focus
    Active-->>Mem: Return active variables
    
    Mem->>STM: Query recent study session logs
    STM-->>Mem: Return recent task logs
    
    Mem->>LTM: Query long-term educational plans & templates
    LTM-->>Mem: Return semantic templates
    
    Mem-->>Plan: Return Compiled Context Window
    deactivate Mem

PART XIX: Reasoning Integration

The Planning Engine integrates with Volume 5's Reasoning Engine to validate
constraints and update internal belief models:

  - Active Belief Updates: Planning steps adjust transition probabilities,
    triggering updates within the Bayesian belief mesh.
  - Causal Risk Audits: The causal reasoning module tests proposed planning
    paths using do-calculus to identify potential side-effects.
  - Safety Rules Checking: Validates plan steps against active policy frameworks
    and user-defined constraints before execution starts.

PART XX: Execution Integration

The Planning Engine dispatches and monitors actions using Volume 2's secure
Execution Engine:

flowchart TD
    A[Approved Planning Lattices] --> B[Execution Planner Compiler]
    B --> C[Allocate worker slot & bind execution port]
    C --> D[Spawn isolated WebAssembly container worker]
    
    D --> E[Execute Action Step payload]
    E --> F[Monitor process telemetry and heartbeats]
    F --> G[Log execution state & return result metrics]

PART XXI: Reflection Integration

Every completed planning run is audited by the Reflection Engine to optimize
future performance templates:

  - Performance Reviews: Traces actual task run metrics (latencies, token costs,
    resource consumption) against planning predictions.
  - Heuristics Synthesizing: Formulates actionable rules from execution
    anomalies or success patterns.
  - Database Consolidation: Writes learned patterns and optimized templates back
    to semantic long-term memory.

PART XXII: Observability

To maintain deep systemic visibility, the Planning Engine generates
OpenTelemetry-compliant logs, spans, and metrics:

  - Span Propagation: Trace identifiers follow planning runs from initial goal
    extraction down to individual container worker tool runs, simplifying
    debugging.
  - Prometheus Metrics: Tracks CPU, memory usage, token throughput, planning
    latencies, and cache hit ratios.
  - Performance Alerts: Automatically logs queue warnings or solver timeout
    events, triggering watchdog processes.

PART XXIII: Configuration

The operational parameters for the Planning Engine are defined in planning.yaml,
outlining thread pools, queue sizes, budget limits, and algorithm parameters.

23.1 Production YAML Configuration (planning.yaml)

version: "2.0.0"
environment: "production"

planning_manager:
  thread_pool_size: 16
  watchdog_interval_ms: 1000
  max_concurrent_sessions: 100
  cancellation_grace_period_ms: 500

queues:
  high_priority_capacity: 50
  active_capacity: 100
  background_capacity: 500
  aging_coefficient: 0.15
  starvation_threshold_ms: 30000

budgets:
  max_token_limit: 150000
  max_execution_time_seconds: 600
  max_cost_limit_usd: 15.00
  memory_limit_mb: 2048

algorithms:
  htn:
    max_recursion_depth: 10
    enable_local_repair: true
  goap:
    max_search_depth: 15
    heuristic_weight: 1.5
  csp:
    solver_timeout_ms: 50
    max_backtracking_iterations: 1500
  simulation:
    monte_carlo_rollouts: 10
    timeout_ms: 250

observability:
  enable_tracing: true
  export_interval_ms: 250
  log_level: "info"

PART XXIV: gRPC APIs

The Planning Engine relies on gRPC over HTTP/2 to communicate across cognitive
subsystems.

24.1 gRPC Protobuf Specification (planning_service.proto)

syntax = "proto3";

package casper.planning.v2;

service PlanningService {
  rpc StartSession(PlanningRequest) returns (PlanningResponse);
  rpc ValidatePlan(ValidationRequest) returns (ValidationResponse);
  rpc RunSimulation(SimulationRequest) returns (SimulationResponse);
  rpc RepairPlan(RepairRequest) returns (RepairResponse);
}

message PlanningRequest {
  string session_id = 1;
  string user_intent = 2;
  double budget_cap_usd = 3;
}

message PlanningResponse {
  string session_id = 1;
  string status_state = 2; // COMPILING, RUNNING, SUCCESSFUL, FAILED
  repeated string execution_nodes = 3;
  double estimated_total_cost = 4;
}

message ValidationRequest {
  string session_id = 1;
  repeated string plan_steps = 2;
}

message ValidationResponse {
  bool is_valid = 1;
  repeated string validation_failures = 2;
  string security_policy_applied = 3;
}

message SimulationRequest {
  string session_id = 1;
  string candidate_step = 2;
}

message SimulationResponse {
  double calculated_success_probability = 1;
  double calculated_risk_score = 2;
  string predicted_outcome_state = 3;
}

message RepairRequest {
  string session_id = 1;
  string failed_step_id = 2;
  string failure_exception = 3;
}

message RepairResponse {
  bool repair_successful = 1;
  repeated string modified_nodes = 2;
}

PART XXV: Performance Engineering

The system enforces strict execution budgets and latency limits across all core
planning layers:

\mathcal{L}_{total} = \mathcal{L}_{intent\_parse} + \mathcal{L}_{decomposition} + \mathcal{L}_{constraints} + \mathcal{L}_{verification} + \mathcal{L}_{dispatch}

Where:

  - \mathcal{L}_{intent\_parse} represents natural language goal normalization
    (\leq 50\text{ms}).
  - \mathcal{L}_{decomposition} represents HTN expansion loops
    (\leq 100\text{ms}).
  - \mathcal{L}_{constraints} represents AC-3 and backtracking CSP solving
    (\leq 20\text{ms}).
  - \mathcal{L}_{verification} represents security and policy verification
    audits (\leq 5\text{ms}).
  - \mathcal{L}_{dispatch} is the port allocation and worker container dispatch
    latency (\leq 10\text{ms}).

PART XXVI: Failure Recovery

                             [FAILURE RECOVERY CORE]
                                        |
         +------------------------------+------------------------------+
         |                              |                              |
         v                              v                              v
[Kernel Panic Watchdog]        [Deadlock Evaluator]           [Corruption Auditing Engine]
 - Identifies subsystem crashes - Scans active queues & locks  - Scans serialized TSB files
 - Reboots isolated structures  - Prunes dependency loops      - Rebuilds context from logs

The system Watchdog manages failures and system crashes, restoring previous
stable states using automated recovery workflows:

  - Subsystem Recovery: If a core planning subsystem crashes, the Watchdog
    isolates the failed component, freezes running queues, reboots the module,
    and restores state from the last saved checkpoint.
  - Pruning Deadlocks: The scheduler scans running queues, running Tarjan's
    cycle-detection loops to identify and break resource locks.
  - Database Failures: If a database file becomes unreadable, the engine rejects
    the corrupt file, reads the incremental backup log, and restores the system
    context.

PART XXVII: Security

To protect host systems and user data, the Planning Engine enforces
multi-layered security boundaries and sandboxing:

flowchart TD
    A[Task Step Compiled] --> B{Verify Privilege Levels}
    
    B -->|High Privilege: payments, file edits| C[Isolate Workspace & Pause Task]
    B -->|Low Privilege: reading, web search| D[Dispatch Task to Sandbox]
    
    C --> E[Generate Biometric Confirmation Gate]
    E -->|User Approved| D
    E -->|User Denied| F[Cancel Task, Rollback, Log Security Alert]

  - Process Sandboxing: Code compilation and command runs execute within
    isolated containers, protecting the host operating system from potential
    exploits or crashes.
  - Inline Sanitization: Outbound payloads are scanned for sensitive personal
    information, redacting private keys or identifiers before data egress.
  - Audit Logs: All planning updates, rule checks, and confirmation logs are
    committed to read-only databases, ensuring complete security audit trails.

PART XXVIII: Testing

The system is validated across development environments using automated testing
pipelines:

  - Chaos Testing: Randomly injects process timeouts, database corruption,
    network drops, and worker crashes to test plan-repair and rollback
    behaviors.
  - Simulation Testing: Employs virtual environments to test agents on
    multi-step workflows, verifying planning and tool coordination.
  - Performance Regression Suites: Tracks execution latencies, resource
    footprint, and token usage to prevent performance degradation over updates.

